and the parseFloat function parses this number as 593 and sorts it this way. The same thing happens when thousand separator is empty space.
My workaround is adding a type check:

```
this.formatFloat = function(s) {
    if(typeof s == 'string') s = s.replace(/[,\s]/g,'');
    var i = parseFloat(s);
    // return the text instead of zero
    return isNaN(i) ? $.trim(s) : i;
};
```
Probably this is bad thing to do, but solves my issue.

