> At some point we want the indexed contents to be more dynamic at runtime.

This really does not make a difference. If there is a single key being used for the entire collection (which is not a great option) that it can perhaps be supplied at the time of booting the replay as an argument. If however different records might have different keys (and some might not have any), but the main CDXJ file does not have them inline, they can be offloaded to a separate key index. Lookup field for the key index file can either be SURT+14DigitDatetime (this can be ambiguous) or the hash of the payload.

```
$ cat index.cdxj
com,example,)/ 20180207132547 {"locator": "urin:ipfs/0123456789...", "encryption": {"method": "external"}, "...": "..."}
com,example,)/bar 20180207172819 {"locator": "urin:ipfs/1029384756...", "...": "..."}
com,example,)/foo 20180207092618 {"locator": "urin:ipfs/9876543210...", "encryption": {"method": "external"}, "...": "..."}

$ cat key.cdxj
0123456789... {"method": "aes", "nonce": "blah", "key": "IWontTellYou"}
9876543210... {"method": "aes", "nonce": "baz", "key": "NoItIsASecret"}
```

This way., when the main index suggests that the content is encrypted but the encryption details can be found from an external source, they supplied keys file should be used for lookup with the corresponding payload hash. This key file can be supplied as an argument when the replay is started the say way an index file is supplied. Also, we may want to never put encryption details in the main index and always keep them in a separate file like this and simply add `"encryption": true` in the index to indicate that the key index should be looked up.

> Can you anticipate the scenario where the client is asked for the key? This may be more fitting and would allow one-off URI-M decryption.

This is again an impractical approach. Even if we somehow try to throw a prompt for the end user to input some keys (such as by initiation an HTTP BasicAuth dialogue), it is going to be frustrating when a single page has hundreds of resources which which those keys are to be asked one by one. Besides, this is not an information the end user should provide one by one. The server has the index, so it has the knowledge of the resource and it should handle any encryption in place. As far as authorization is concerned, that should be dealt in a separate layer between the client and the server.

